# UCAB - MVC Pattern

## Overview

The UCAB Cab Booking Application follows the Model-View-Controller (MVC) architecture pattern. MVC separates the application into three independent layers, improving maintainability, scalability, and code organization.

---

## Model Layer (Data Layer)

The Model layer manages all database-related operations using MongoDB and Mongoose.

### Responsibilities

- Define database schemas
- Perform CRUD operations
- Validate data
- Store and retrieve application data

### Models

- User Model
- Driver Model
- Ride Model
- Payment Model

---

## Controller Layer

Controllers act as intermediaries between Routes and Models.

### Responsibilities

- Receive requests
- Process business logic
- Validate user input
- Communicate with models
- Return responses

### Examples

- User Registration Controller
- Login Controller
- Ride Booking Controller
- Payment Controller

---

## View Layer (Routing Layer)

The View layer is implemented through API Routes.

### Responsibilities

- Define API endpoints
- Handle HTTP requests
- Call controller functions
- Return responses

### Example Routes

POST /api/users/register

POST /api/users/login

POST /api/rides/book

GET /api/rides/history

PUT /api/rides/update

DELETE /api/rides/cancel

---

## MVC Workflow

1. User sends request from React Frontend.
2. Route receives the request.
3. Controller processes the request.
4. Controller interacts with Model.
5. Model communicates with MongoDB.
6. Data is returned to Controller.
7. Response is sent back to Frontend.

---

## Advantages of MVC

- Separation of Concerns
- Better Code Organization
- Easy Maintenance
- Scalability
- Reusability
- Easy Testing
- Team Collaboration

---

## Outcome

MVC architecture helps UCAB maintain a clean and scalable code structure while simplifying development and maintenance.

Project: UCAB Cab Booking System

Technology Stack: MERN Stack
